'''Dagbani music and dance''' is a core tradition of the [[Dagomba people|Dagbamba]] or Dagomba people. The [[Dagomba people|Dagbamba]] speak the Dagbani (more appriopriately [[Dagbani language|Dagbanli]]) language. They are the dominant [[Ethnic groups in Africa#Overview#Western Africa|ethnic group]] in the [[chiefdom]] of [[Dagomba people#Kingdom of Dagbon|Dagbon]] found in the [[Northern Region, Ghana|Northern Region]] of [[Ghana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/149693/Dagomba-kingdom|title=Dagomba kingdom|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica |author=|year=1994|accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref> Music and dance plays a central role in [[Dagomba people#Kingdom of Dagbon|Dagbon]]. It is through these arts that the [[Dagomba people|Dagbamba]] have preserved their history over the centuries. The [[Dagomba people|Dagbamba]] regard dancing as a form of emotional expression, social interaction, a spiritual performance or even physical exercise that aids them articulate or illustrate ideas or tell a story. In most cases, music in [[Dagomba people#Kingdom of Dagbon|Dagbon]] is accompanied by dancing in order to form a complete story.
==Music in Dagbon== [[File:The National Archives UK - CO 1069-46-39.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A weaver plies his craft at Flyboyiri (1957)]] Dagbani music is best known for an extremely advanced drumming tradition{{who|date=January 2014}}, especially using the lunga and gungon.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}
==Dancing in Dagbon== {{expand section|date=January 2014}} Dagbon music is usually composed specifically to facilitate or accompany dancing.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}
==Contemporary Music and Dance== The [[Dagomba people|Dagbamba]] have embraced and incorporated modern forms of music though traditional dagbani music and dancing can still be witnessed at formal congregations and at Universities around the world . Locally, it has become much easier to hear [[Dagbani language|Dagbanli]] music in non-traditional genres like [[Reggae]], [[Hip hop]], [[Hiplife]] or [[Islamic music]]. On very rare occasions non-traditional [[Dagbani language|Dagbanli]] music is blended with traditional elements such as drumming.
Modern artistes who perform in [[Dagbani language|Dagbanli]] include [[Sherifa Gunu]], R2bees, Sherif Ghaale, and [[Awal Alhassan]].
The [[rhythm game]] series [[Just Dance (video game series)|Just Dance]] features the sound track "Dagomba" in their games. Composed by Sorcerer, the song [[Sampling (music)|samples]] music of the Dagomba people.
